{"annotations": [{"id": ["mesh:D016202"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "N-methyl-D-aspartate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992583394050598, "span": {"begin": 0, "end": 20}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2902"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9231683611869812, "span": {"begin": 0, "end": 37}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016202"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NMDA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987154603004456, "span": {"begin": 22, "end": 26}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:18420"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Mg2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998617172241211, "span": {"begin": 141, "end": 145}}, {"id": ["mesh:D018698"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glutamate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.994461178779602, "span": {"begin": 167, "end": 176}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012640"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "seizure", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.6791178584098816, "span": {"begin": 270, "end": 277}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:18420"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Mg2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9999127388000488, "span": {"begin": 311, "end": 315}}, {"id": ["CL:0000540"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neuron", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.3718668520450592, "span": {"begin": 361, "end": 367}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016202"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NMDA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995827078819275, "span": {"begin": 388, "end": 392}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2902"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NMDA receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9717153310775757, "span": {"begin": 388, "end": 401}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013226"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "status epilepticus", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.994023859500885, "span": {"begin": 606, "end": 624}}], "text": "N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors are ligand and voltage-gated receptors. They require both a post-synaptic depolarization to remove the Mg2+ block and binding of glutamate for receptor activation (Kandel et al., 2013). High frequency stimulation that occurs during seizure activity aides in removal of the Mg2+ block through depolarization of the affected neuron. The conditions for NMDA receptor activation are ideal as there is prolonged firing and overall increased depolarization during seizure activity (Kapur, 2018). Sustainment of seizure activity for greater than 5 minutes&nbsp;develops into status epilepticus (McDonough and Shih, 1997).   &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:15:34 +0000 2026"}